<subSubSection pageId="87" pageNumber="87" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="87.[128,658,1124,1763]" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">
IDENTIFICATION: Descriptions and measurements of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[241,470,1300,1323]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliense">
<emphasis box="[241,470,1300,1323]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">Tonatia brasiliense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Guianas and elsewhere can be found in 
<bibRefCitation author="Goodwin, G. G." journalOrPublisher="J. Mammal." pageId="87" pageNumber="87" pagination="204 - 209" part="23" refId="ref94213" refString="Goodwin, G. G. 1942. A summary of recognizable species of Tonatia, with descriptions of two new species. J. Mammal. 23: 204 - 209." title="A summary of recognizable species of Tonatia, with descriptions of two new species" type="journal article" year="1942">Goodwin (1942)</bibRefCitation>
, Swanepoel and 
<bibRefCitation author="Genoways, H. H. &amp; S. L. Williams" box="[432,652,1358,1381]" journalOrPublisher="Ann. Carnegie Mus." pageId="87" pageNumber="87" pagination="323 - 335" part="48" refId="ref93773" refString="Genoways, H. H., and S. L. Williams 1979. Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname. Ann. Carnegie Mus. 48: 323 - 335." title="Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname" type="journal article" year="1979">Genoways (1979)</bibRefCitation>
, Genoways and Williams (1984), and 
<bibRefCitation author="Brosset, A. &amp; P. Charles-Dominique" journalOrPublisher="Mammalia" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" pagination="509 - 559" part="54" refId="ref91807" refString="Brosset, A., and P. Charles-Dominique 1990. The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach. Mammalia 54: 509 - 559." title="The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach" type="journal article" year="1990">Brosset and Charles­Dominique (1990)</bibRefCitation>
. No subspecies are currently recognized (Genoways and Williams, 1984; Koopman, 1994).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="87.[128,658,1124,1763]" lastBlockId="87.[704,1233,214,1381]" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">
As the smallest member of its genus, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">Tonatia brasiliense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most likely to be confused with species of 
<taxonomicName box="[311,474,1564,1587]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Micronycteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[311,474,1564,1587]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">Micronycteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which are also small gray­brown phyllostomines with large, rounded ears. Genoways and Williams (1984) mentioned several craniodental characters that can be used to distinguish these taxa, but failed to note one obvious external character: whereas all species of 
<emphasis box="[536,756,215,1763]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">Micronyc­ teris</emphasis>
have a pair of large dermal pads forming a ‘‘V’’ on the tip of the chin, the tip of the chin in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[846,1009,273,296]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliense">
<emphasis box="[846,862,273,296]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[881,1009,273,296]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">brasiliense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(and other congeners) has a U­shaped row of tiny dermal papillae (
<bibRefCitation author="Emmons, L. H." box="[790,976,332,355]" journalOrPublisher="Chicago: Univ. Chicago Press" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" refId="ref92899" refString="Emmons, L. H. 1990. Neotropical rainforest mammals: a field guide. Chicago: Univ. Chicago Press." title="Neotropical rainforest mammals: a field guide" type="book" year="1990">Emmons, 1990</bibRefCitation>
, 1997). We also observed that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[845,1007,361,384]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliense">
<emphasis box="[845,861,361,384]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[879,1007,361,384]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">brasiliense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
folds its ears back against the crown of the head when touched, a behavior seen in several other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[704,794,449,472]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[704,794,449,472]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">Tonatia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below) but not in 
<taxonomicName box="[1063,1226,449,472]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Micronycteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1063,1226,449,472]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">Micronycteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="87.[704,1233,214,1381]" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">
Our voucher material conforms closely with previous descriptions of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">Tonatia brasiliense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, particularly those based on material from the Guianas. Probably because our series contains more individuals than do earlier collections from the region, it exhibits somewhat greater size variability than previously reported. However, measurements of our specimens fall within the range of variation previously documented for the species as a whole.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="87.[704,1233,214,1381]" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">
As remarked by Genoways and Williams (1984), 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[799,1028,831,854]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliense">
<emphasis box="[799,1028,831,854]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">Tonatia brasiliense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as currently recognized may be composite. Should this prove to be the case, comparisons with published measurements (e.g., those in 
<bibRefCitation author="Goodwin, G. G." journalOrPublisher="J. Mammal." pageId="87" pageNumber="87" pagination="204 - 209" part="23" refId="ref94213" refString="Goodwin, G. G. 1942. A summary of recognizable species of Tonatia, with descriptions of two new species. J. Mammal. 23: 204 - 209." title="A summary of recognizable species of Tonatia, with descriptions of two new species" type="journal article" year="1942">Goodwin [1942]</bibRefCitation>
and Swanepoel and 
<bibRefCitation author="Genoways, H. H. &amp; S. L. Williams" journalOrPublisher="Ann. Carnegie Mus." pageId="87" pageNumber="87" pagination="323 - 335" part="48" refId="ref93773" refString="Genoways, H. H., and S. L. Williams 1979. Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname. Ann. Carnegie Mus. 48: 323 - 335." title="Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname" type="journal article" year="1979">Genoways [1979]</bibRefCitation>
) suggest that our specimens, along with others from the Guianas, would be referred to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[821,984,1036,1059]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliense">
<emphasis box="[821,837,1036,1059]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[856,984,1036,1059]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">brasiliense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rather than to other taxa currently treated as synonyms (e.g., 
<taxonomicName class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Micronycteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[766,898,1095,1118]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">nicaraguae</emphasis>
, and 
<emphasis box="[982,1109,1095,1118]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">venezuelae</emphasis>
; Handley [1966], Gardner [1976], 
<bibRefCitation author="Jones, J. K., Jr. &amp; D. C. Carter" editor="Baker, J. K. &amp; Jones, Jr. &amp; D. C. Carter" journalOrPublisher="Biology of bats of the New World family Phyllostomidae, pt. 1: 7 - 38. Spec. Publ. Mus. Texas Tech Univ." pageId="87" pageNumber="87" part="10" refId="ref96048" refString="Jones, J. K., Jr., and D. C. Carter 1976. Annotated checklist with keys to subfamilies and genera. In R. J. Baker, J. K. Jones, Jr., and D. C. Carter (eds.), Biology of bats of the New World family Phyllostomidae, pt. 1: 7 - 38. Spec. Publ. Mus. Texas Tech Univ. 10." title="Annotated checklist with keys to subfamilies and genera" type="journal volume" volumeTitle="R. J" year="1976">Jones and Carter [1976]</bibRefCitation>
, Genoways and Williams [1984], 
<bibRefCitation author="Medellin, R. A. &amp; H. T. Arita" bookContentInfo="5 pp." journalOrPublisher="Mamm. Species 334" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" refId="ref98027" refString="Medellin, R. A., and H. T. Arita 1989. Tonatia evotis and Tonatia silvicola. Mamm. Species 334: 5 pp." title="Tonatia evotis and Tonatia silvicola" type="book" year="1989">Medellín and Arita [1989]</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Koopman, K. F." box="[1025,1227,1182,1205]" editor="D. E. Wilson &amp; D. M. Reeder" journalOrPublisher="Washington, DC: Smithson. Inst. Press" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" refId="ref96667" refString="1993. Order Chiroptera. In D. E. Wilson and D. M. Reeder (eds.), Mammal species of the World, a taxonomic and geographic reference, 2 nd ed.: 137 - 241. Washington, DC: Smithson. Inst. Press." title="Order Chiroptera" type="book" volumeTitle="Mammal species of the World, a taxonomic and geographic reference, 2 nd" year="1993">Koopman [1993</bibRefCitation>
, 1994]).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="87" pageNumber="87" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="87.[704,1233,214,1381]" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">
FIELD OBSERVATIONS: All of the nine specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[819,1047,1271,1294]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="87" pageNumber="87" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brasiliense">
<emphasis box="[819,1047,1271,1294]" italics="true" pageId="87" pageNumber="87">Tonatia brasiliense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that we caught at Paracou were taken in ground­level mistnets: six in swampy primary forest and three in creekside primary forest.
</paragraph>
